    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="193"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d193">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.00/2372.</note>
                <pb facs="0297" n="181" xml:id="pg_181"/>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Hale</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">San José</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 7, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s December 4. I could hear nothing whatever of General Mena until this
                    morning, when the Panama papers of November 30 brought news of his arrival there
                    the day before and of his intention to visit Punta Arenas or Port Limon in a few
                    days. San José paper this evening records his arrival here last evening in an
                    “ordinary passenger train” and devotes half a dozen lines to a description of
                    him.</p>
                <p>I do not think there is the slightest reason to believe that he is receiving aid
                    from the Costa Rican Government.</p>
                <p>My despatch No. 48 [47], November 30, mentioned the gathering here of Julian
                    Irias and half a dozen Nicaraguan generals; but I have been so far unable to
                    ascertain their purpose. Whatever the [omission in transmission], their meeting
                    in this particular place signifies [omission in transmission], for San Jose is
                    the asylum of political refugees.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hale</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
